The `ppc_bc` instruction has a 14-bit signed displacement (bits 15:2). The mask `0xFFFC` keeps bits 15:2. But if `off` is larger than `0x7FFC` (32764 bytes), the displacement overflows! A JIT block could be up to `BLK_WDS * 4 = (64*160+512)*4 ≈ 43008` bytes... no wait, `BLK_WDS = BLK_ARMS*160+512 = 64*160+512 = 10752` words = 43008 bytes. That's WAY larger than 32KB. So `off` could easily exceed the 14-bit branch range!

When `off` overflows the 14-bit field, the branch goes to the wrong address. If the emitted branch target wraps around to `0x000E2B04`, that would explain the crash.

**This is the bug.** The `ppc_bc` instruction's displacement is only **14 bits** (15:2), allowing a range of ±32KB. But JIT blocks can be much larger than 32KB, so the patched branch displacement can overflow.

Here is the complete fix. The solution is to use **long conditional branches** (invert the condition, branch-over a long `b` instruction) instead of relying on the 14-bit `ppc_bc` displacement for large blocks:

```cpp
// jit_ppc.cpp - TARGETED FIX for branch displacement overflow
// All other code remains the same as the previous fix.
// Only the branch emission and patching system changes.

// ============================================================
// Branch patching — safe for arbitrarily large blocks
//
// Instead of a single ppc_bc with a 14-bit displacement (±32KB),
// we emit a 3-instruction sequence when a conditional skip is needed:
//
//   bc  inv_cond, bi, +8    ; if condition MET, skip over the b
//   b   target              ; unconditional 24-bit branch (±32MB)
//   [fall-through code]
//
// Or for forward patching where we don't know the target yet:
//   bc  inv_cond, bi, +8    ; skip over the b if condition is TRUE
//   b   placeholder         ; 24-bit branch, patched later
//
// The 24-bit `b` instruction covers ±32MB which is more than enough
// for any JIT block.
// ============================================================

// Unconditional PPC branch instruction
static inline uint32_t ppc_b(int32_t off, bool lk=false){
    // off must be multiple of 4, within ±32MB
    return (18u<<26) | ((uint32_t)(off & 0x03FFFFFC)) | (lk?1u:0u);
}

// Emit a conditional skip over subsequent code.
// Returns the index of the `b` instruction (24-bit) that needs patching.
// Returns SIZE_MAX for AL (always) or unsupported conditions.
//
// Emits:
//   [idx-1] bc inv_cond, bi, +8   ; if condition TRUE, skip the b
//   [idx]   b  0                   ; placeholder, patched by patchSkip
static size_t emitCondSkip(Ctx& ctx, uint8_t cond){
    if(cond == 14) return SIZE_MAX;  // AL: never skip
    emitLoadCR7(ctx);
    CB cb = condPpc(cond);
    if(!cb.ok) return SIZE_MAX;  // complex condition: caller falls back

    // Emit: bc inv_cond, bi, +8  (skip over the 'b' if condition TRUE)
    // The +8 skips 2 instructions: the bc itself (+4) and the b (+4) = +8 from bc.
    uint8_t inv = (cb.bo == 12) ? 4u : 12u;
    ctx.E(ppc_bc(inv, cb.bi, 8));    // branch +8 if condition TRUE (skip the 'b')

    // Emit placeholder `b 0` — will be patched to branch past the block
    size_t idx = ctx.sz();
    ctx.E(ppc_b(0));                 // placeholder: b to fall-through (condition FALSE)
    return idx;
}

static void patchSkip(Ctx& ctx, size_t idx){
    if(idx == SIZE_MAX) return;
    // idx is the index of the `b` instruction.
    // We patch it to branch from its own position to ctx.sz().
    int32_t off = (int32_t)((ctx.sz() - idx) * 4);  // distance from `b` to current position
    // Verify range (±32MB = ±0x2000000)
    if(off > 0x1FFFFFC || off < -0x2000000){
        // Block is impossibly large; this shouldn't happen with BLK_ARMS=64
        // Emit a nop and accept the bug (or assert)
        ctx.base[idx] = ppc_nop();
        return;
    }
    ctx.base[idx] = ppc_b(off);
}
```

